/* CCSP :: content/quiz4.js — CCSP Domain 4 question bank (100 items). */
window.CCSP = window.CCSP || {}; CCSP.questions = CCSP.questions || [];
CCSP.questions.push.apply(CCSP.questions, [{"id":"D4-001","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"easy","q":"A cloud development team lead wants to give new hires a single, community-maintained reference to the most critical categories of web application security risks. Which resource is the best fit?","options":["The OWASP Top 10","The NIST National Vulnerability Database","The MITRE ATT&CK enterprise matrix","The CIS Controls v8"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The OWASP Top 10</strong> — it is the community-maintained, awareness-focused list of the most critical web application security risk categories, exactly what new developers should study first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The NIST National Vulnerability Database</b>: it is a catalog of specific CVEs, not a curated awareness list of risk categories for developer training.</span><span class='qd'><b>The MITRE ATT&CK enterprise matrix</b>: it models adversary tactics and techniques for detection engineering, not application code-level risk categories.</span><span class='qd'><b>The CIS Controls v8</b>: it is an enterprise security-control baseline, broader than application code risks and not developer-awareness focused.</span>"},{"id":"D4-002","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"easy","q":"During code review, an analyst finds a query built by concatenating unvalidated user input directly into a database call. Which OWASP Top 10 category does this most directly represent?","options":["Security Misconfiguration","Injection","Cryptographic Failures","Vulnerable and Outdated Components"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Injection</strong> — concatenating untrusted input into a database query is the textbook SQL injection flaw, squarely within the Injection category.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Security Misconfiguration</b>: that covers insecure defaults, verbose errors, and unhardened settings, not untrusted data reaching an interpreter.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic Failures</b>: that concerns weak or missing encryption of sensitive data, not query construction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerable and Outdated Components</b>: that concerns using libraries with known flaws, not a coding error in query building.</span>"},{"id":"D4-003","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"medium","q":"A SaaS team stores API secrets in a public source-code repository so builds can run without extra setup. A security advisor flags this as a common cloud development pitfall. What is the primary risk being called out?","options":["Increased build latency from repository size","Loss of code portability between clouds","Exposure of credentials leading to unauthorized access","Reduced test coverage of the CI pipeline"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Exposure of credentials leading to unauthorized access</strong> — hardcoding secrets in repositories is a classic cloud pitfall because anyone with repo access (or a public mirror) can harvest the keys and access cloud resources.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increased build latency from repository size</b>: performance is not the security concern; a few keys add negligible size.</span><span class='qd'><b>Loss of code portability between clouds</b>: portability is unrelated to where secrets are stored.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduced test coverage of the CI pipeline</b>: secret placement does not change test coverage.</span>"},{"id":"D4-004","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"medium","q":"An attacker submits a crafted request that causes a server-side application to fetch a URL pointing at the cloud provider's internal metadata endpoint, revealing instance credentials. Which vulnerability class best describes this?","options":["Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","Broken Access Control","Insecure Deserialization","Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)</strong> — tricking the server into making an attacker-controlled request to an internal endpoint (like the instance metadata service) is the defining pattern of SSRF and a notorious cloud-specific pitfall.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)</b>: XSS executes scripts in a victim's browser, not server-side fetches to internal endpoints.</span><span class='qd'><b>Broken Access Control</b>: while credential exposure follows, the mechanism here is the forged server-side request, which is SSRF specifically.</span><span class='qd'><b>Insecure Deserialization</b>: that abuses untrusted serialized objects, not URL fetching by the server.</span>"},{"id":"D4-005","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"easy","q":"Which reference is most appropriate for enumerating the most dangerous software weaknesses at the source-code level, such as CWE categories developers should avoid?","options":["The SANS/CWE Top 25 Most Dangerous Software Weaknesses","The Cloud Controls Matrix (CCM)","ISO/IEC 27018","FIPS 140-3"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The SANS/CWE Top 25 Most Dangerous Software Weaknesses</strong> — it enumerates the most impactful code-level weaknesses (CWEs), making it the developer-facing companion to the OWASP list.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The Cloud Controls Matrix (CCM)</b>: it is a control framework for cloud governance, not a code-weakness catalog.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27018</b>: it addresses PII protection in public clouds, unrelated to code weaknesses.</span><span class='qd'><b>FIPS 140-3</b>: it validates cryptographic modules, not software weakness categories.</span>"},{"id":"D4-006","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"hard","q":"A microservices team relies on a popular open-source library that recently had a critical deserialization CVE published. Ops has not updated it in eight months. Under OWASP Top 10, which category most precisely captures the exposure, and why is it acute in cloud CI/CD?","options":["Injection, because deserialization passes data to an interpreter","Vulnerable and Outdated Components, because unpatched dependencies propagate through automated image builds","Security Logging and Monitoring Failures, because the CVE was published","Identification and Authentication Failures, because service accounts are involved"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Vulnerable and Outdated Components, because unpatched dependencies propagate through automated image builds</strong> — the root exposure is an unpatched dependency, and in cloud CI/CD the flawed library is baked into every container image and replicated at scale.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Injection, because deserialization passes data to an interpreter</b>: the immediate issue is that the component is unpatched, not that the team wrote injection-prone code.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security Logging and Monitoring Failures, because the CVE was published</b>: publication of a CVE does not describe a logging gap.</span><span class='qd'><b>Identification and Authentication Failures, because service accounts are involved</b>: no authentication weakness is described in the scenario.</span>"},{"id":"D4-007","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"medium","q":"A developer new to cloud assumes that because the provider secures the hypervisor, application-layer input validation is unnecessary. Which foundational concept has the developer misunderstood?","options":["Rapid elasticity","Measured service","The shared responsibility model","Resource pooling"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The shared responsibility model</strong> — the provider secures the underlying platform, but the customer remains responsible for securing their own application code, including input validation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rapid elasticity</b>: that describes scaling capacity, not who secures which layer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Measured service</b>: that describes metered, pay-per-use billing, unrelated to security duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Resource pooling</b>: that describes multi-tenant resource sharing, not the split of security obligations.</span>"},{"id":"D4-008","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"easy","q":"An application returns a full stack trace, including framework versions and file paths, to end users when an error occurs. Which OWASP Top 10 category does this best illustrate?","options":["Cryptographic Failures","Software and Data Integrity Failures","Injection","Security Misconfiguration"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Security Misconfiguration</strong> — verbose error messages that leak internal details to users are a classic misconfiguration, aiding reconnaissance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic Failures</b>: no encryption weakness is involved in leaking a stack trace.</span><span class='qd'><b>Software and Data Integrity Failures</b>: that concerns unverified updates and CI/CD tampering, not error verbosity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Injection</b>: no untrusted data is reaching an interpreter here.</span>"},{"id":"D4-009","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud-native app grants any authenticated user the ability to change the account ID in an API path and view another tenant's records. Which OWASP Top 10 category is this?","options":["Broken Access Control","Cryptographic Failures","Vulnerable and Outdated Components","Security Logging and Monitoring Failures"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Broken Access Control</strong> — allowing a user to manipulate an identifier to reach data they are not authorized for (an IDOR-style flaw) is the leading Broken Access Control pattern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic Failures</b>: the data was not protected by authorization, not by faulty encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vulnerable and Outdated Components</b>: no third-party component flaw is described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security Logging and Monitoring Failures</b>: the issue is unauthorized access, not a detection gap.</span>"},{"id":"D4-010","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"hard","q":"A DevOps engineer argues that awareness training for developers should emphasize cloud-specific pitfalls over generic ones. Which pairing is the strongest example of a genuinely cloud-amplified pitfall versus a generic one?","options":["Buffer overflow versus off-by-one error","Overly permissive IAM roles and exposed storage buckets versus a missing semicolon","Weak password hashing versus using deprecated TLS","Race condition versus integer overflow"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Overly permissive IAM roles and exposed storage buckets versus a missing semicolon</strong> — misconfigured IAM and public object storage are quintessential cloud-amplified pitfalls, whereas a syntax slip is generic and caught at build time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Buffer overflow versus off-by-one error</b>: both are generic memory-safety issues, neither uniquely cloud-amplified.</span><span class='qd'><b>Weak password hashing versus using deprecated TLS</b>: both are cryptographic hygiene issues that exist on-prem too.</span><span class='qd'><b>Race condition versus integer overflow</b>: both are generic concurrency/arithmetic bugs, not cloud-specific.</span>"},{"id":"D4-011","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"medium","q":"A team wants a single artifact that enumerates all third-party and open-source components in a build so that when a new CVE lands they can instantly tell whether they are affected. What should they generate?","options":["A data flow diagram","A threat model report","A software bill of materials (SBOM)","A penetration test scope statement"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A software bill of materials (SBOM)</strong> — an SBOM inventories every component and version, enabling instant impact assessment when a new component vulnerability is disclosed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A data flow diagram</b>: it maps how data moves for threat modeling, not a component inventory.</span><span class='qd'><b>A threat model report</b>: it documents threats and mitigations, not a dependency list.</span><span class='qd'><b>A penetration test scope statement</b>: it defines test boundaries, not software composition.</span>"},{"id":"D4-012","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"easy","q":"Which statement best captures why input validation remains a developer responsibility even in a fully managed PaaS environment?","options":["The PaaS provider validates all application inputs by contract","Managed platforms eliminate the need for secure coding","Input validation is only relevant for on-premises systems","Input validation defends against injection and abuse that the platform cannot see inside the app logic"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Input validation defends against injection and abuse that the platform cannot see inside the app logic</strong> — the platform cannot know the semantics of your application's inputs, so validation stays with the developer.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The PaaS provider validates all application inputs by contract</b>: providers secure the platform, not your business-logic inputs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Managed platforms eliminate the need for secure coding</b>: managed services reduce infrastructure burden but never remove secure-coding duties.</span><span class='qd'><b>Input validation is only relevant for on-premises systems</b>: injection risks are identical or worse in cloud-exposed apps.</span>"},{"id":"D4-013","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"easy","q":"In a secure software development lifecycle, at which phase should security requirements first be formally captured?","options":["During the requirements/definition phase","During deployment","After the first penetration test","During maintenance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>During the requirements/definition phase</strong> — capturing security requirements at the start ensures they drive design and are testable, embodying security-by-design.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>During deployment</b>: waiting until deployment means requirements were never designed in, forcing costly retrofits.</span><span class='qd'><b>After the first penetration test</b>: a pen test validates controls late; requirements must precede design and testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>During maintenance</b>: maintenance is far too late for foundational security requirements.</span>"},{"id":"D4-014","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"medium","q":"A regulated financial customer needs predictable milestones, heavy up-front documentation, and formal sign-off gates between phases for a cloud application. Which SDLC methodology best matches these business requirements?","options":["Extreme Programming (XP)","Waterfall","Kanban","Rapid prototyping"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Waterfall</strong> — its sequential phases with formal gates and heavy documentation match a regulated environment demanding predictable milestones and sign-offs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Extreme Programming (XP)</b>: XP is agile and iterative, favoring adaptability over up-front documentation and gates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Kanban</b>: Kanban emphasizes continuous flow, not phase-gated milestones.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rapid prototyping</b>: it prioritizes quick throwaway builds over documentation and formal sign-off.</span>"},{"id":"D4-015","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"medium","q":"An agile cloud team releases every two weeks and wants security to keep pace rather than becoming a phase-end bottleneck. Which practice best aligns security with their methodology?","options":["Scheduling a single security review just before each annual release","Deferring all threat modeling to the maintenance phase","Integrating automated security testing into the CI/CD pipeline for every sprint","Requiring a manual change-advisory board approval for each commit"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Integrating automated security testing into the CI/CD pipeline for every sprint</strong> — embedding automated checks per sprint shifts security left and keeps pace with iterative delivery.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Scheduling a single security review just before each annual release</b>: an annual gate defeats the point of two-week iterations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deferring all threat modeling to the maintenance phase</b>: threat modeling belongs in design, not after release.</span><span class='qd'><b>Requiring a manual change-advisory board approval for each commit</b>: per-commit manual gates would stall continuous delivery.</span>"},{"id":"D4-016","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"easy","q":"Which SDLC phase is primarily concerned with correcting defects, applying patches, and retiring the application at end of life?","options":["Design","Testing","Requirements","Maintenance and disposal"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Maintenance and disposal</strong> — ongoing patching, defect correction, and eventual secure decommissioning are the responsibilities of the maintenance/disposal phase.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Design</b>: design produces architecture and specifications, not ongoing patching.</span><span class='qd'><b>Testing</b>: testing validates the build before release, not lifetime upkeep.</span><span class='qd'><b>Requirements</b>: requirements define what to build, not how it is maintained or retired.</span>"},{"id":"D4-017","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"medium","q":"A product owner insists that security is a non-functional requirement that can be added after the functional features are complete. Why is this reasoning flawed from a secure-SDLC perspective?","options":["Security requirements shape architecture and are far cheaper to design in than to bolt on later","Non-functional requirements are always optional","Functional requirements are handled by the cloud provider","Security only matters during penetration testing"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Security requirements shape architecture and are far cheaper to design in than to bolt on later</strong> — defects fixed in design cost a fraction of those fixed post-release, and security influences fundamental architecture choices.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Non-functional requirements are always optional</b>: many non-functional requirements (security, availability) are mandatory.</span><span class='qd'><b>Functional requirements are handled by the cloud provider</b>: the customer owns their application's functional requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security only matters during penetration testing</b>: security spans the entire lifecycle, not a single test.</span>"},{"id":"D4-018","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is choosing between waterfall and agile for a greenfield cloud application whose regulatory requirements are still being negotiated and are expected to change repeatedly. Which choice best serves the business requirement, and why?","options":["Waterfall, because regulated projects always require sequential phases","Agile, because iterative cycles accommodate evolving requirements while still allowing security to be embedded each sprint","Waterfall, because changing requirements make documentation impossible in agile","Agile, because it removes the need for any security requirements"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Agile, because iterative cycles accommodate evolving requirements while still allowing security to be embedded each sprint</strong> — when requirements are volatile, agile's short feedback loops adapt continuously, and DevSecOps lets security stay embedded.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Waterfall, because regulated projects always require sequential phases</b>: regulation does not mandate waterfall, and locking requirements early fails when they keep changing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Waterfall, because changing requirements make documentation impossible in agile</b>: agile still produces documentation; it just does so iteratively.</span><span class='qd'><b>Agile, because it removes the need for any security requirements</b>: agile never removes security requirements; it distributes them across sprints.</span>"},{"id":"D4-019","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"medium","q":"Which artifact produced during the design phase most directly enables the later testing phase to verify that security controls behave as intended?","options":["The release notes","The final invoice from the cloud provider","Documented, testable security requirements and acceptance criteria","The user marketing brief"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Documented, testable security requirements and acceptance criteria</strong> — testable requirements give the testing phase concrete, verifiable criteria to check controls against.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The release notes</b>: release notes summarize changes after the fact, not testable criteria.</span><span class='qd'><b>The final invoice from the cloud provider</b>: billing is irrelevant to control verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>The user marketing brief</b>: marketing material does not define security acceptance criteria.</span>"},{"id":"D4-020","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of gathering business requirements before designing a cloud application?","options":["To select the cheapest possible cloud region","To bypass the testing phase","To eliminate the need for a change management process","To ensure the solution's functional and security needs align with organizational goals and constraints"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To ensure the solution's functional and security needs align with organizational goals and constraints</strong> — requirements gathering aligns what is built with real business, compliance, and security needs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To select the cheapest possible cloud region</b>: cost is one constraint, not the primary purpose of requirements gathering.</span><span class='qd'><b>To bypass the testing phase</b>: requirements never justify skipping testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for a change management process</b>: change management remains necessary regardless of requirements.</span>"},{"id":"D4-021","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"medium","q":"A security architect wants a threat-modeling methodology whose acronym maps threats to Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information disclosure, Denial of service, and Elevation of privilege. Which methodology is this?","options":["STRIDE","DREAD","PASTA","ATASM"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>STRIDE</strong> — its six letters map exactly to Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information disclosure, Denial of service, and Elevation of privilege.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>DREAD</b>: DREAD is a risk-rating scheme (Damage, Reproducibility, Exploitability, Affected users, Discoverability), not a threat-category taxonomy.</span><span class='qd'><b>PASTA</b>: PASTA is a seven-stage attack-simulation process, not the STRIDE mnemonic.</span><span class='qd'><b>ATASM</b>: ATASM (Architecture, Threats, Attack Surfaces, Mitigations) is an architecture-driven flow, not the STRIDE categories.</span>"},{"id":"D4-022","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"medium","q":"A team needs to prioritize discovered threats by scoring damage potential, reproducibility, exploitability, affected users, and discoverability. Which methodology provides this rating model?","options":["STRIDE","DREAD","Data flow diagramming","SAST"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>DREAD</strong> — its five factors (Damage, Reproducibility, Exploitability, Affected users, Discoverability) form a scoring model for prioritizing threats.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>STRIDE</b>: STRIDE categorizes threat types but does not score or rank them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data flow diagramming</b>: DFDs help identify threats, not rate their severity.</span><span class='qd'><b>SAST</b>: static analysis finds code flaws; it is not a threat-prioritization model.</span>"},{"id":"D4-023","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud security team wants a risk-centric, seven-stage threat modeling process that begins with defining business objectives and ends with residual-risk analysis, explicitly aligning technical threats to business impact. Which methodology fits best?","options":["STRIDE","DREAD","PASTA","OWASP ASVS"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>PASTA</strong> — the Process for Attack Simulation and Threat Analysis is a seven-stage, risk-centric method that starts from business objectives and drives to residual-risk analysis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>STRIDE</b>: STRIDE is a threat-category taxonomy, not a seven-stage business-aligned process.</span><span class='qd'><b>DREAD</b>: DREAD only scores individual threats; it is not a full multi-stage process.</span><span class='qd'><b>OWASP ASVS</b>: ASVS is a verification standard for controls, not a threat-modeling process.</span>"},{"id":"D4-024","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"medium","q":"When applying threat modeling to a cloud application, which artifact should typically be produced first to establish where trust boundaries and data flows exist?","options":["A penetration test report","A disaster recovery runbook","A software license inventory","A data flow diagram (DFD) with trust boundaries"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A data flow diagram (DFD) with trust boundaries</strong> — mapping data flows and trust boundaries is the foundation that lets threats be identified at each crossing point.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A penetration test report</b>: a pen test comes after design and validates the running system, not the modeling starting point.</span><span class='qd'><b>A disaster recovery runbook</b>: DR planning is a separate operational concern from threat modeling.</span><span class='qd'><b>A software license inventory</b>: licensing is a supply-chain concern, not a threat-modeling foundation.</span>"},{"id":"D4-025","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which resource provides a tiered catalog of application security verification requirements that developers can use as a secure-coding checklist across levels of assurance?","options":["OWASP ASVS (Application Security Verification Standard)","NIST CSF","ISO/IEC 27001 Annex A","The MITRE ATT&CK matrix"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>OWASP ASVS (Application Security Verification Standard)</strong> — ASVS provides tiered, testable security requirements developers use as a secure-coding and verification checklist.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>NIST CSF</b>: the Cybersecurity Framework is an enterprise risk-management framework, not an app-verification checklist.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27001 Annex A</b>: it lists organizational controls, not developer-level verification requirements.</span><span class='qd'><b>The MITRE ATT&CK matrix</b>: it catalogs adversary techniques, not secure-coding verification levels.</span>"},{"id":"D4-026","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"medium","q":"A serverless function trusts a JWT claim to decide administrative privilege without re-validating the token signature server-side. During threat modeling, which STRIDE category most precisely captures this weakness?","options":["Denial of service","Elevation of privilege","Repudiation","Tampering"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Elevation of privilege</strong> — accepting a forgeable claim to grant admin rights lets a low-privilege actor gain elevated access, the essence of Elevation of privilege.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Denial of service</b>: no availability impact is described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Repudiation</b>: repudiation concerns the inability to prove who did an action, not privilege gain.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tampering</b>: while a forged token involves tampering, the security outcome being modeled is unauthorized privilege elevation.</span>"},{"id":"D4-027","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"hard","q":"An architect uses an architecture-first threat method that decomposes the system, then enumerates threats and attack surfaces before mapping mitigations, and is especially suited to reasoning about cloud reference architectures. Which method is described?","options":["DREAD","Fuzzing","ATASM","SCA"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>ATASM</strong> — Architecture, Threats, Attack Surfaces, Mitigations is the architecture-first flow that decomposes a system before enumerating threats and surfaces, well suited to cloud architectures.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>DREAD</b>: DREAD scores threats but does not decompose architecture or map attack surfaces.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fuzzing</b>: fuzzing is a dynamic testing technique, not a threat-modeling method.</span><span class='qd'><b>SCA</b>: software composition analysis inspects dependencies, not architecture threat flow.</span>"},{"id":"D4-028","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"medium","q":"A team wants to guarantee that every change to application code is tracked, attributable, and reversible, and that build inputs are known and consistent. Which practice most directly delivers this?","options":["Blue-green deployment","Horizontal autoscaling","Content delivery network caching","Software configuration management with version control"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Software configuration management with version control</strong> — SCM and versioning make every change tracked, attributable, reversible, and reproducible.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Blue-green deployment</b>: it reduces release risk but does not by itself track or attribute code changes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Horizontal autoscaling</b>: it adjusts capacity, unrelated to change tracking.</span><span class='qd'><b>Content delivery network caching</b>: caching improves delivery performance, not change control.</span>"},{"id":"D4-029","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which industry resource offers language-agnostic secure coding practices and fundamental principles authored by a consortium of software vendors?","options":["SAFECode secure development practices","The PCI DSS SAQ","ISO/IEC 27017","The FedRAMP SSP template"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>SAFECode secure development practices</strong> — SAFECode publishes vendor-consortium, language-agnostic secure development guidance and fundamental practices.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The PCI DSS SAQ</b>: it is a payment-card self-assessment questionnaire, not secure-coding guidance.</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO/IEC 27017</b>: it provides cloud security controls, not developer coding practices.</span><span class='qd'><b>The FedRAMP SSP template</b>: it documents a system's security controls for authorization, not coding practices.</span>"},{"id":"D4-030","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"hard","q":"During threat modeling of a multi-tenant SaaS platform, the team identifies that one tenant could potentially read another tenant's cached objects due to a shared cache key namespace. Which cloud-specific risk category and mitigation pairing is most appropriate?","options":["Data remanence; overwrite the disk seven times","Multi-tenancy isolation failure; enforce tenant-scoped cache keys and logical partitioning","Vendor lock-in; adopt an open cache protocol","Denial of service; add rate limiting"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Multi-tenancy isolation failure; enforce tenant-scoped cache keys and logical partitioning</strong> — cross-tenant data bleed from a shared namespace is an isolation failure, remedied by scoping keys per tenant and partitioning logically.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data remanence; overwrite the disk seven times</b>: remanence concerns leftover data on media, not live cross-tenant cache reads.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor lock-in; adopt an open cache protocol</b>: lock-in is a portability concern unrelated to tenant isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Denial of service; add rate limiting</b>: rate limiting addresses availability, not confidentiality between tenants.</span>"},{"id":"D4-031","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"medium","q":"A developer wants to avoid the common vulnerability where user-supplied data is rendered into a web page without encoding. Which secure-coding control is the primary defense?","options":["Increasing the session timeout","Enabling gzip compression","Output encoding/context-aware escaping","Adding a CAPTCHA to the login page"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Output encoding/context-aware escaping</strong> — encoding untrusted data for the rendering context is the primary defense against cross-site scripting.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the session timeout</b>: timeouts affect session lifetime, not XSS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enabling gzip compression</b>: compression is a performance feature, irrelevant to encoding.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adding a CAPTCHA to the login page</b>: CAPTCHAs deter automation at login, not script injection into output.</span>"},{"id":"D4-032","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"medium","q":"When applying the secure SDLC to a cloud application, why is threat modeling most valuable when performed during the design phase rather than after deployment?","options":["It reduces the cloud bill","It replaces the need for penetration testing entirely","It is only useful for on-premises architectures","It identifies design-level flaws while they are cheapest to fix and before code is written"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It identifies design-level flaws while they are cheapest to fix and before code is written</strong> — design-phase threat modeling catches architectural flaws early, avoiding expensive post-deployment rework.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It reduces the cloud bill</b>: cost savings are incidental, not the security purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for penetration testing entirely</b>: modeling and testing are complementary, not substitutes.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is only useful for on-premises architectures</b>: threat modeling applies equally, arguably more, to cloud designs.</span>"},{"id":"D4-033","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following best defines a trust boundary in a threat model?","options":["A point where data or requests move between components of differing privilege or trust levels","The physical perimeter of the data center","The maximum number of concurrent users","The SLA availability target"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A point where data or requests move between components of differing privilege or trust levels</strong> — trust boundaries mark transitions in privilege/trust and are where threats concentrate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical perimeter of the data center</b>: threat-model trust boundaries are logical, not physical fences.</span><span class='qd'><b>The maximum number of concurrent users</b>: that is a capacity metric, not a trust concept.</span><span class='qd'><b>The SLA availability target</b>: an SLA figure is unrelated to trust transitions.</span>"},{"id":"D4-034","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"medium","q":"A security tester analyzes source code without executing it to find flaws early in the pipeline. Which testing methodology is being used?","options":["Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)","Penetration testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Static Application Security Testing (SAST)</strong> — SAST inspects source or binaries without executing them, enabling early, white-box detection of flaws.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)</b>: DAST tests a running application from the outside, not static source.</span><span class='qd'><b>Interactive Application Security Testing (IAST)</b>: IAST instruments a running app to observe behavior, so it requires execution.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration testing</b>: pen testing exercises the live system, not static code analysis.</span>"},{"id":"D4-035","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"medium","q":"A team runs automated attacks against a deployed, running web application from the outside, with no access to source, to find exploitable runtime flaws. Which methodology is this?","options":["SAST","SCA","DAST","Code review"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>DAST</strong> — Dynamic Application Security Testing probes a running application externally (black-box) to find runtime-exploitable flaws.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SAST</b>: SAST examines static code, not a running deployment.</span><span class='qd'><b>SCA</b>: software composition analysis inspects dependencies, not live runtime behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>Code review</b>: manual code review reads source, it does not attack a running app.</span>"},{"id":"D4-036","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"easy","q":"Which testing methodology specifically identifies known-vulnerable and outdated open-source dependencies in an application?","options":["Fuzz testing","Load testing","Usability testing","Software Composition Analysis (SCA)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Software Composition Analysis (SCA)</strong> — SCA inventories third-party and open-source components and flags those with known vulnerabilities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fuzz testing</b>: fuzzing sends malformed inputs to find crashes, not dependency CVEs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load testing</b>: load testing measures performance under stress, not component vulnerabilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Usability testing</b>: usability testing evaluates user experience, unrelated to dependencies.</span>"},{"id":"D4-037","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"hard","q":"A security lead wants continuous, real-time detection of vulnerabilities during functional QA by instrumenting the running application with agents that observe code execution as tests exercise it. Which methodology best fits, and why is it distinct from SAST and DAST?","options":["IAST, because it combines runtime instrumentation with code-level visibility during execution","SAST, because it reads code without executing it","DAST, because it attacks from outside with no internal visibility","SCA, because it inspects dependency manifests"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>IAST, because it combines runtime instrumentation with code-level visibility during execution</strong> — Interactive Application Security Testing instruments the app so it sees both runtime behavior and the underlying code path as tests run, blending SAST and DAST strengths.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SAST, because it reads code without executing it</b>: SAST lacks runtime context; the scenario requires observing execution.</span><span class='qd'><b>DAST, because it attacks from outside with no internal visibility</b>: DAST is black-box and cannot see code paths during execution.</span><span class='qd'><b>SCA, because it inspects dependency manifests</b>: SCA analyzes components, not live code execution during QA.</span>"},{"id":"D4-038","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"medium","q":"During assurance testing, a QA engineer deliberately designs test cases that model how a malicious user would misuse a feature, such as replaying a password-reset token. What type of testing is this?","options":["Regression testing","Abuse-case (misuse-case) testing","Smoke testing","Compatibility testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Abuse-case (misuse-case) testing</strong> — modeling how an attacker would misuse functionality is exactly abuse-case testing, complementing positive functional tests.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Regression testing</b>: regression confirms existing features still work after changes, not adversarial misuse.</span><span class='qd'><b>Smoke testing</b>: smoke testing checks basic build sanity, not attacker behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compatibility testing</b>: compatibility checks environments/platforms, not malicious misuse.</span>"},{"id":"D4-039","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"easy","q":"Which pairing correctly distinguishes functional from non-functional testing?","options":["Functional: measuring latency; Non-functional: verifying correct output","Functional: encryption strength; Non-functional: business logic correctness","Functional: verifying login works; Non-functional: measuring how fast login responds under load","Functional: scalability limits; Non-functional: feature behavior"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Functional: verifying login works; Non-functional: measuring how fast login responds under load</strong> — functional testing checks whether features behave correctly; non-functional testing checks qualities like performance, scalability, and security under conditions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Functional: measuring latency; Non-functional: verifying correct output</b>: this reverses the definitions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Functional: encryption strength; Non-functional: business logic correctness</b>: encryption strength is a non-functional quality and logic correctness is functional, so this is reversed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Functional: scalability limits; Non-functional: feature behavior</b>: scalability is non-functional and feature behavior is functional, so this is reversed.</span>"},{"id":"D4-040","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud team wants their security testing to catch flaws as early and cheaply as possible in the CI pipeline while a developer is still writing code. Which combination is best positioned earliest (shift-left)?","options":["Penetration testing and red-team exercises","Production DAST scans only","Post-incident forensic analysis","SAST and SCA integrated into the developer's commit/build stage"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>SAST and SCA integrated into the developer's commit/build stage</strong> — static analysis and composition analysis run without a deployed app, so they fit earliest in the pipeline, embodying shift-left.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration testing and red-team exercises</b>: these require a running target and occur late, not at commit time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Production DAST scans only</b>: DAST needs a deployed running app, so it cannot run earliest.</span><span class='qd'><b>Post-incident forensic analysis</b>: forensics is reactive, occurring after an incident, not during coding.</span>"},{"id":"D4-041","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"hard","q":"A vendor delivers a compiled binary with no source access, and the customer must still gain confidence in its security before deployment. Which testing approach is most applicable, and why?","options":["Black-box DAST and fuzzing, because they require no source and probe the running/binary behavior","White-box SAST, because the customer can read every line of source","IAST, because the customer can instrument the vendor's build pipeline","Formal code review, because the source is available"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Black-box DAST and fuzzing, because they require no source and probe the running/binary behavior</strong> — with only a binary, black-box dynamic testing and fuzzing are applicable since they need no source code.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>White-box SAST, because the customer can read every line of source</b>: no source is available, so SAST is not feasible.</span><span class='qd'><b>IAST, because the customer can instrument the vendor's build pipeline</b>: the customer has no access to the vendor's pipeline or source to instrument.</span><span class='qd'><b>Formal code review, because the source is available</b>: the premise states there is no source access.</span>"},{"id":"D4-042","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"medium","q":"A QA process passes an application only when defined security acceptance criteria are met alongside functional criteria. What role does this quality assurance gate primarily serve in the secure SDLC?","options":["It guarantees zero vulnerabilities forever","It validates that the software meets its stated functional and security requirements before release","It replaces the requirements phase","It eliminates the need for monitoring in production"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It validates that the software meets its stated functional and security requirements before release</strong> — the QA gate confirms the build satisfies both functional and security acceptance criteria before it ships.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees zero vulnerabilities forever</b>: no gate can guarantee the perpetual absence of vulnerabilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the requirements phase</b>: QA verifies against requirements; it does not replace defining them.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for monitoring in production</b>: production monitoring remains essential post-release.</span>"},{"id":"D4-043","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"easy","q":"Which statement best describes fuzz testing?","options":["Reviewing source code line by line for logic errors","Measuring application response time under peak load","Sending large volumes of malformed or random input to a program to trigger crashes or unexpected behavior","Confirming the UI renders correctly across browsers"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Sending large volumes of malformed or random input to a program to trigger crashes or unexpected behavior</strong> — fuzzing bombards inputs with malformed data to surface crashes, memory errors, and unhandled edge cases.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reviewing source code line by line for logic errors</b>: that describes manual code review, not fuzzing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Measuring application response time under peak load</b>: that is performance/load testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Confirming the UI renders correctly across browsers</b>: that is compatibility testing.</span>"},{"id":"D4-044","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"hard","q":"A security architect reviews a pipeline that runs only SAST. Which residual gap is the strongest justification for adding DAST as well?","options":["SAST cannot read source code","DAST is faster to run than SAST in every case","SAST already covers dependency license compliance","DAST detects runtime and environment/configuration flaws that only manifest when the application is deployed and executing"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>DAST detects runtime and environment/configuration flaws that only manifest when the application is deployed and executing</strong> — SAST cannot see runtime behavior or deployment configuration, so DAST fills that gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SAST cannot read source code</b>: SAST's defining trait is that it does read source code.</span><span class='qd'><b>DAST is faster to run than SAST in every case</b>: speed varies and is not the justification for coverage.</span><span class='qd'><b>SAST already covers dependency license compliance</b>: license compliance is an SCA concern, and it does not justify adding DAST.</span>"},{"id":"D4-045","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud provider restricts customer-initiated penetration testing of shared services without prior authorization. What is the most appropriate action for a customer who needs a pen test performed?","options":["Obtain provider authorization and scope the test per the provider's rules of engagement","Proceed without notice since the customer owns the application","Rely solely on the provider's internal testing and never test the application","Test only the provider's underlying hypervisor"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Obtain provider authorization and scope the test per the provider's rules of engagement</strong> — in shared, multi-tenant clouds, pen testing must be authorized and scoped to the customer's own assets per the provider's rules of engagement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Proceed without notice since the customer owns the application</b>: unauthorized testing can violate contracts and disrupt other tenants.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on the provider's internal testing and never test the application</b>: the customer still needs assurance over its own application layer.</span><span class='qd'><b>Test only the provider's underlying hypervisor</b>: the hypervisor is the provider's responsibility and off-limits to the customer.</span>"},{"id":"D4-046","domain":4,"obj":"4.4","diff":"medium","q":"During testing, a team must confirm that a newly patched authentication module did not break previously working single sign-on flows. Which type of testing addresses this need?","options":["Fuzz testing","Regression testing","Abuse-case testing","Penetration testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Regression testing</strong> — regression testing re-verifies that existing functionality (the SSO flows) still works after a change such as a patch.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fuzz testing</b>: fuzzing hunts for crashes on malformed input, not preservation of existing flows.</span><span class='qd'><b>Abuse-case testing</b>: abuse-case testing models attacker misuse, not verification that prior features still work.</span><span class='qd'><b>Penetration testing</b>: pen testing seeks exploitable weaknesses, not regression of features.</span>"},{"id":"D4-047","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"medium","q":"A team applying the secure SDLC to a container-based cloud app wants to reduce the risk that a compromised build injects malicious code into the image. Which control most directly addresses software and data integrity in the pipeline?","options":["Increasing container CPU limits","Switching from JSON to YAML manifests","Signing artifacts and verifying signatures before deployment","Enabling verbose application logging"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Signing artifacts and verifying signatures before deployment</strong> — cryptographically signing build artifacts and verifying them before deploy ensures integrity and blocks tampered images.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing container CPU limits</b>: resource limits affect performance, not build integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Switching from JSON to YAML manifests</b>: manifest format has no bearing on artifact integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enabling verbose application logging</b>: logging aids detection but does not prevent malicious code injection into the image.</span>"},{"id":"D4-048","domain":4,"obj":"4.1","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud application accepts serialized objects from clients and reconstructs them server-side without integrity checks, allowing an attacker to craft objects that execute code on reconstruction. Which OWASP category is most precise, and what is the core defect?","options":["Cryptographic Failures; sensitive data was not encrypted","Security Misconfiguration; the server used default settings","Broken Access Control; the user lacked authorization","Software and Data Integrity Failures / Insecure Deserialization; untrusted serialized data is deserialized without integrity verification"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Software and Data Integrity Failures / Insecure Deserialization; untrusted serialized data is deserialized without integrity verification</strong> — deserializing untrusted objects without integrity checks is the insecure-deserialization defect within Software and Data Integrity Failures.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic Failures; sensitive data was not encrypted</b>: the flaw is trusting untrusted serialized input, not a missing-encryption issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security Misconfiguration; the server used default settings</b>: no default-settings misconfiguration is described; the defect is in handling serialized input.</span><span class='qd'><b>Broken Access Control; the user lacked authorization</b>: the exploit does not hinge on missing authorization checks but on unsafe deserialization.</span>"},{"id":"D4-049","domain":4,"obj":"4.2","diff":"hard","q":"An organization adopting DevSecOps wants security embedded so that a failed security test can block a release just as a failed unit test would. Which principle most accurately describes what they are implementing?","options":["Shifting security left and treating security gates as first-class pipeline stages","Security as a manual, post-release audit","Delegating all security to the cloud provider","Testing security only in the maintenance phase"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Shifting security left and treating security gates as first-class pipeline stages</strong> — making security tests gate releases alongside unit tests embeds security early and continuously, the core of DevSecOps shift-left.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Security as a manual, post-release audit</b>: a post-release manual audit is the opposite of embedding security into the pipeline.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delegating all security to the cloud provider</b>: the customer still owns application security under shared responsibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Testing security only in the maintenance phase</b>: confining security to maintenance defeats shift-left.</span>"},{"id":"D4-050","domain":4,"obj":"4.3","diff":"easy","q":"Why is applying the principle of least privilege to service accounts especially important when building cloud applications?","options":["It increases application throughput","It limits the blast radius if an application component or credential is compromised","It removes the need for logging","It guarantees regulatory compliance automatically"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It limits the blast radius if an application component or credential is compromised</strong> — least privilege confines what a compromised component or leaked credential can reach, reducing impact.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It increases application throughput</b>: least privilege is a security control, not a performance optimization.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need for logging</b>: logging remains essential for detection and forensics regardless.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees regulatory compliance automatically</b>: it supports compliance but does not automatically guarantee it.</span>"},{"id":"D4-051","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"easy","q":"A development team wants to trust an open-source library that has not been reviewed. Which practice best supports the goal of using verified secure software?","options":["Pick whichever library has the most GitHub stars","Fork the library and stop pulling upstream updates","Adopt only libraries with active maintainers, published CVE history, and reproducible builds","Trust the library because it compiles without warnings"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Adopt only libraries with active maintainers, published CVE history, and reproducible builds</strong> — verified secure software means the component's provenance, maintenance, and vulnerability posture are evaluated before adoption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pick whichever library has the most GitHub stars</b>: popularity is not a security assurance; stars say nothing about vulnerabilities or maintenance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fork the library and stop pulling upstream updates</b>: this strands you on an unpatched version and increases risk over time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trust the library because it compiles without warnings</b>: compilation success is unrelated to the presence of exploitable flaws.</span>"},{"id":"D4-052","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"easy","q":"An architect must protect a public web application from SQL injection and cross-site scripting at the HTTP layer. Which supplemental security component is the best fit?","options":["Database activity monitor (DAM)","XML gateway","API rate limiter only","Web application firewall (WAF)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Web application firewall (WAF)</strong> — a WAF inspects HTTP/HTTPS requests and blocks common web attacks such as SQLi and XSS at the application layer.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Database activity monitor (DAM)</b>: DAM watches database queries and privileged DB access, not inbound HTTP payloads.</span><span class='qd'><b>XML gateway</b>: this is specialized for XML/SOAP message validation, not general web-layer SQLi/XSS.</span><span class='qd'><b>API rate limiter only</b>: rate limiting curbs abuse volume but does not parse or block injection content.</span>"},{"id":"D4-053","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"easy","q":"Employees complain about maintaining separate passwords for many SaaS apps. Which IAM capability directly reduces the number of times they must authenticate?","options":["Single sign-on (SSO)","Data loss prevention (DLP)","Full-disk encryption","Network segmentation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Single sign-on (SSO)</strong> — SSO lets a user authenticate once to an identity provider and access many applications without re-entering credentials.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data loss prevention (DLP)</b>: DLP controls sensitive-data movement, not authentication frequency.</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk encryption</b>: this protects data at rest on a device and has nothing to do with app logins.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network segmentation</b>: segmentation limits lateral movement, not the count of authentication events.</span>"},{"id":"D4-054","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"A company wants users at a partner organization to access its cloud app using the partner's own directory, without provisioning local accounts. Which model should the architect implement?","options":["Shared service account","Federated identity","Local database authentication","Static API keys per user"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Federated identity</strong> — federation establishes trust between identity domains so the partner's IdP asserts identities the relying app accepts, with no local account creation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Shared service account</b>: shared accounts break accountability and non-repudiation and are not per-user identity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Local database authentication</b>: this requires provisioning and managing local accounts, exactly what federation avoids.</span><span class='qd'><b>Static API keys per user</b>: keys are credentials to issue and rotate locally, not a trust relationship between directories.</span>"},{"id":"D4-055","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A microservices platform exposes dozens of internal APIs. Security wants a single enforcement point for authentication, throttling, and request validation. Which component best centralizes this?","options":["Service mesh sidecar logging","Reverse-proxy cache","API gateway","Host-based IDS"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>API gateway</strong> — a gateway provides a unified ingress that authenticates, rate-limits, validates, and routes API calls, centralizing cross-cutting controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Service mesh sidecar logging</b>: logging is observability, not a single policy enforcement point for auth and throttling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reverse-proxy cache</b>: caching improves performance but does not enforce authentication or validation policy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Host-based IDS</b>: HIDS detects host anomalies; it is not an API traffic control plane.</span>"},{"id":"D4-056","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"medium","q":"Before integrating a third-party payment SDK, a security architect wants assurance about the vendor's own controls. Which artifact most directly supports supply-chain vendor assessment?","options":["The vendor's marketing datasheet","A screenshot of the vendor's login page","The SDK's minified source bundle","A SOC 2 Type II report and SBOM for the SDK"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A SOC 2 Type II report and SBOM for the SDK</strong> — an independent controls report plus a software bill of materials gives evidence of the vendor's security posture and component provenance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor's marketing datasheet</b>: marketing material is unverified self-promotion, not assurance evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screenshot of the vendor's login page</b>: a UI image tells you nothing about internal controls or dependencies.</span><span class='qd'><b>The SDK's minified source bundle</b>: minified code alone is not an assessment and obscures rather than assures.</span>"},{"id":"D4-057","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"easy","q":"To reduce account takeover from stolen passwords, which control adds a second authentication factor?","options":["MFA","SSO","TLS","DLP"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>MFA</strong> — multi-factor authentication requires an additional factor (something you have or are) so a stolen password alone is insufficient.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SSO</b>: SSO reduces login prompts but does not by itself add a second factor.</span><span class='qd'><b>TLS</b>: TLS secures data in transit, not the authentication factor count.</span><span class='qd'><b>DLP</b>: DLP inspects data movement and is unrelated to authentication.</span>"},{"id":"D4-058","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"hard","q":"A CISO wants visibility and policy enforcement over sanctioned and shadow SaaS usage, including inline blocking of risky uploads. Which solution is purpose-built for this?","options":["Hardware security module (HSM)","Cloud access security broker (CASB)","Container registry scanner","DNSSEC resolver"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Cloud access security broker (CASB)</strong> — a CASB sits between users and cloud services to discover shadow IT, apply policy, and inspect/block risky data flows inline or via API.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hardware security module (HSM)</b>: an HSM protects keys; it does not broker SaaS access or enforce upload policy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Container registry scanner</b>: this scans images for vulnerabilities, not user SaaS behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>DNSSEC resolver</b>: DNSSEC validates DNS integrity, not application data-movement policy.</span>"},{"id":"D4-059","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A team runs untrusted user-submitted code as part of a cloud feature. Which architectural technique best contains the blast radius if that code is malicious?","options":["Increasing the VM memory allocation","Enabling verbose logging only","Sandboxing the execution environment","Adding a WAF in front of the API"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Sandboxing the execution environment</strong> — a sandbox isolates untrusted code with constrained permissions and resources so a compromise cannot reach the host or other tenants.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the VM memory allocation</b>: more memory does nothing to contain malicious behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enabling verbose logging only</b>: logging aids detection after the fact but provides no containment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adding a WAF in front of the API</b>: a WAF filters HTTP requests but does not isolate code already executing internally.</span>"},{"id":"D4-060","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"hard","q":"During a supply-chain review, an analyst finds a build pulls dependencies from an unpinned public registry at build time. Which risk is most acute, and what remediation applies?","options":["Data-at-rest exposure; enable disk encryption","SQL injection; deploy a WAF","Session fixation; shorten token lifetime","Dependency confusion / substitution; pin versions and use an internal proxy with integrity checks"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Dependency confusion / substitution; pin versions and use an internal proxy with integrity checks</strong> — unpinned public pulls let an attacker publish a malicious same-named package; pinning and a curated proxy with hash verification close the gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data-at-rest exposure; enable disk encryption</b>: encryption addresses storage confidentiality, not build-time package substitution.</span><span class='qd'><b>SQL injection; deploy a WAF</b>: a WAF protects runtime HTTP, not the software supply chain during builds.</span><span class='qd'><b>Session fixation; shorten token lifetime</b>: token lifetime is a session concern unrelated to dependency sourcing.</span>"},{"id":"D4-061","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"An application currently embeds database passwords in configuration files committed to source control. What is the most appropriate remediation?","options":["Move credentials to a secrets management service with rotation and least-privilege access","Base64-encode the passwords in the file","Rename the file to hide it","Comment out the passwords when not needed"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Move credentials to a secrets management service with rotation and least-privilege access</strong> — a secrets manager stores credentials outside code, controls access, and enables rotation and auditing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Base64-encode the passwords in the file</b>: encoding is trivially reversible and provides no protection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rename the file to hide it</b>: obscurity does not prevent access and the secret remains in history.</span><span class='qd'><b>Comment out the passwords when not needed</b>: commented secrets still sit in the repository and version history.</span>"},{"id":"D4-062","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A legacy partner integration exchanges SOAP messages with complex XML. Security wants to validate schemas and block XML-based attacks like entity expansion. Which component fits best?","options":["Standard WAF signature set","XML gateway (XML firewall)","Database activity monitor","TLS termination proxy"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>XML gateway (XML firewall)</strong> — an XML gateway validates XML schemas and defends against XML-specific attacks such as XXE and entity expansion.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Standard WAF signature set</b>: general WAF rules are not tailored to deep XML/SOAP structure validation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Database activity monitor</b>: DAM observes database access, not SOAP message content.</span><span class='qd'><b>TLS termination proxy</b>: terminating TLS handles encryption, not XML payload validation.</span>"},{"id":"D4-063","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"hard","q":"In a SAML-based federation, the relying party wants to guarantee that an assertion was actually issued by the trusted IdP and was not altered in transit. What primarily provides this guarantee?","options":["The assertion's session cookie","The user's password complexity","The IdP's digital signature on the assertion","The service provider's TLS certificate alone"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The IdP's digital signature on the assertion</strong> — the SP validates the signature against the IdP's known public key, confirming authenticity and integrity of the assertion.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The assertion's session cookie</b>: cookies track sessions and do not prove issuer authenticity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The user's password complexity</b>: password strength is unrelated to verifying the assertion's origin.</span><span class='qd'><b>The service provider's TLS certificate alone</b>: TLS protects the channel but does not authenticate the IdP-issued assertion payload.</span>"},{"id":"D4-064","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"medium","q":"A REST API returns detailed stack traces and internal object IDs in error responses. From an API security standpoint, what is the primary concern?","options":["Improved developer experience","Faster response times","Better SEO ranking","Excessive data exposure aiding attacker reconnaissance"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Excessive data exposure aiding attacker reconnaissance</strong> — verbose errors leak internal structure and IDs that help attackers map the system and craft exploits like IDOR.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Improved developer experience</b>: convenience for developers is not a security justification and belongs in non-production only.</span><span class='qd'><b>Faster response times</b>: verbose errors do not improve performance and are irrelevant to the concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Better SEO ranking</b>: error verbosity has no bearing on search ranking and ignores the leak.</span>"},{"id":"D4-065","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"easy","q":"An organization is decomposing a monolith into independently deployable services communicating over APIs. This architectural style is best described as:","options":["Microservices","Mainframe batch processing","Client-side rendering","Peer-to-peer file sharing"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Microservices</strong> — microservices architecture composes an application from small, independently deployable services that communicate over lightweight APIs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Mainframe batch processing</b>: this is a legacy centralized model, the opposite of decomposed services.</span><span class='qd'><b>Client-side rendering</b>: that describes where UI is rendered, not service decomposition.</span><span class='qd'><b>Peer-to-peer file sharing</b>: P2P is a distribution topology unrelated to application service architecture.</span>"},{"id":"D4-066","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud team wants short-lived, automatically rotated credentials for service-to-service calls instead of long-lived static keys. Which approach best meets this goal?","options":["Hard-coded API keys shared across services","Workload identity with dynamically issued short-lived tokens from a secrets/identity service","A single admin password for all services","Disabling authentication between internal services"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Workload identity with dynamically issued short-lived tokens from a secrets/identity service</strong> — dynamic short-lived tokens tied to workload identity minimize exposure and remove standing static secrets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hard-coded API keys shared across services</b>: shared static keys are long-lived, hard to rotate, and break accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single admin password for all services</b>: one shared secret maximizes blast radius and violates least privilege.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling authentication between internal services</b>: removing auth abandons zero-trust principles and invites lateral movement.</span>"},{"id":"D4-067","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"hard","q":"A vendor delivers a commercial component but refuses to share any SBOM or vulnerability data, citing IP concerns. Which contract/assurance mechanism best reduces the residual risk of adopting it?","options":["Accept the component without conditions to avoid delay","Rely solely on the vendor's verbal assurances","Require independent third-party security testing results and source-code escrow with a right-to-audit clause","Disable all logging around the component to reduce noise"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Require independent third-party security testing results and source-code escrow with a right-to-audit clause</strong> — independent testing plus escrow and audit rights give assurance and recourse without forcing full SBOM disclosure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept the component without conditions to avoid delay</b>: this transfers no risk and leaves the organization blind.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on the vendor's verbal assurances</b>: unverifiable promises are not assurance evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable all logging around the component to reduce noise</b>: removing telemetry worsens detection and does not address supply-chain risk.</span>"},{"id":"D4-068","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A database supporting a SaaS product must be watched for anomalous privileged queries and potential exfiltration by insiders. Which supplemental control is most appropriate?","options":["Web application firewall","API gateway throttling","Client-side input validation","Database activity monitoring (DAM)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Database activity monitoring (DAM)</strong> — DAM observes and alerts on database queries and privileged activity independent of the application, catching insider misuse and exfiltration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Web application firewall</b>: a WAF inspects HTTP at the app edge, not direct database sessions.</span><span class='qd'><b>API gateway throttling</b>: throttling limits request volume but does not analyze query behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>Client-side input validation</b>: client validation is easily bypassed and cannot monitor DB activity.</span>"},{"id":"D4-069","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"easy","q":"Which entity in a federation is responsible for authenticating the user and issuing identity assertions?","options":["Identity provider (IdP)","Service provider (relying party)","Certificate revocation list","Load balancer"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Identity provider (IdP)</strong> — the IdP authenticates the user and issues signed assertions/tokens that relying parties consume.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Service provider (relying party)</b>: the SP consumes assertions; it does not authenticate the user in federation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certificate revocation list</b>: a CRL lists revoked certificates and issues no identity assertions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancer</b>: a load balancer distributes traffic and plays no identity role.</span>"},{"id":"D4-070","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"hard","q":"A container orchestration platform hosts multiple tenants. To limit the damage of a compromised container, which combination of controls is most aligned with secure cloud application architecture?","options":["Run all containers as root on a shared kernel with no policies","Apply least-privilege pod security, network policies, and namespace isolation with image signing","Grant every container access to the host filesystem for convenience","Disable image scanning to speed deployments"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Apply least-privilege pod security, network policies, and namespace isolation with image signing</strong> — layered isolation, restricted privileges, verified images, and segmented networking contain a compromised container.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Run all containers as root on a shared kernel with no policies</b>: root plus no policy maximizes blast radius on a shared kernel.</span><span class='qd'><b>Grant every container access to the host filesystem for convenience</b>: host mounts enable escape and cross-tenant impact.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable image scanning to speed deployments</b>: skipping scanning lets known-vulnerable images ship.</span>"},{"id":"D4-071","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"easy","q":"What does an SBOM (software bill of materials) primarily provide to a cloud security team?","options":["A network topology diagram","A list of user accounts","An inventory of components and dependencies in a software product","A backup schedule"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>An inventory of components and dependencies in a software product</strong> — an SBOM enumerates the libraries and versions inside software so teams can assess and track vulnerabilities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A network topology diagram</b>: topology describes infrastructure, not software composition.</span><span class='qd'><b>A list of user accounts</b>: accounts are an IAM artifact, unrelated to component inventory.</span><span class='qd'><b>A backup schedule</b>: backup cadence is an operations concern, not a bill of materials.</span>"},{"id":"D4-072","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"An organization adopts OIDC for its customer-facing app. Which statement best describes what OIDC adds on top of OAuth 2.0?","options":["It replaces TLS with its own transport encryption","It eliminates the need for an authorization server","It is a database encryption standard","It adds an authentication/identity layer (ID token) on top of OAuth authorization"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It adds an authentication/identity layer (ID token) on top of OAuth authorization</strong> — OIDC extends OAuth 2.0 with a standardized ID token so relying parties can verify who the user is, not just delegated access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces TLS with its own transport encryption</b>: OIDC still relies on TLS for transport security.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for an authorization server</b>: OIDC still uses an authorization/identity server to issue tokens.</span><span class='qd'><b>It is a database encryption standard</b>: OIDC is an identity protocol, not a storage encryption spec.</span>"},{"id":"D4-073","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A serverless function processes uploaded files and calls several downstream APIs. Which cryptographic practice best protects sensitive fields end to end regardless of intermediate hops?","options":["Apply application-layer (field-level) encryption to sensitive data","Rely only on network TLS between hops","Store data unencrypted and restrict logging","Encrypt only the function's environment variables"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Apply application-layer (field-level) encryption to sensitive data</strong> — encrypting the sensitive fields themselves keeps them protected across every hop and at rest, independent of transport.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely only on network TLS between hops</b>: TLS protects a single hop and exposes plaintext at each endpoint.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store data unencrypted and restrict logging</b>: leaving data unencrypted fails confidentiality outright.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt only the function's environment variables</b>: env-var encryption protects config, not the sensitive payload fields.</span>"},{"id":"D4-074","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"hard","q":"A CI pipeline signs artifacts, but the signing keys live on the same shared runner that untrusted PR builds execute on. What supply-chain weakness does this create, and the best fix?","options":["No weakness; shared runners are fine","Key theft by malicious PR code; isolate signing to a hardened, restricted runner or HSM-backed signer","Slow builds; increase runner CPU","Merge conflicts; enforce squash commits"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Key theft by malicious PR code; isolate signing to a hardened, restricted runner or HSM-backed signer</strong> — untrusted builds sharing the signing environment can exfiltrate keys; signing must be isolated with protected key custody.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>No weakness; shared runners are fine</b>: co-locating secrets with untrusted execution is a classic supply-chain flaw.</span><span class='qd'><b>Slow builds; increase runner CPU</b>: performance is irrelevant to the key-exposure risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Merge conflicts; enforce squash commits</b>: commit hygiene does not address signing-key theft.</span>"},{"id":"D4-075","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"An administrator needs elevated access only during scheduled maintenance windows and wants approvals and time limits enforced. Which IAM concept best applies?","options":["Standing permanent admin rights","Shared root credentials","Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access with approval and expiry","Anonymous access for maintenance"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Just-in-time (JIT) privileged access with approval and expiry</strong> — JIT grants elevated rights temporarily upon approval and revokes them automatically, minimizing standing privilege.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Standing permanent admin rights</b>: permanent elevation is exactly the risk JIT removes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Shared root credentials</b>: sharing root destroys accountability and least privilege.</span><span class='qd'><b>Anonymous access for maintenance</b>: anonymity prevents attribution and violates access control.</span>"},{"id":"D4-076","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"easy","q":"Which supplemental control is specifically designed to enforce authentication, quotas, and routing for API traffic entering a cloud application?","options":["Full-disk encryption","Syslog server","Antivirus agent","API gateway"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>API gateway</strong> — an API gateway manages API ingress with authentication, quotas/throttling, and routing in one control point.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk encryption</b>: FDE protects data at rest on disks, not API traffic policy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Syslog server</b>: syslog collects logs; it does not enforce API access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Antivirus agent</b>: AV scans endpoints for malware, not API request policy.</span>"},{"id":"D4-077","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"medium","q":"An open-source dependency is discovered to have a critical CVE with a patched release available. Following verified-secure-software practice, what is the best immediate action?","options":["Test and deploy the patched version, and update the SBOM","Ignore it because the app has a WAF","Remove all logging to hide the vulnerable version","Wait for the next major release cycle"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Test and deploy the patched version, and update the SBOM</strong> — remediating known vulnerable components promptly and keeping the SBOM current is core to using verified secure software.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore it because the app has a WAF</b>: a WAF is not a substitute for patching a known critical flaw.</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove all logging to hide the vulnerable version</b>: hiding evidence does not fix the vulnerability and harms detection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Wait for the next major release cycle</b>: delaying leaves a critical, exploitable flaw in production.</span>"},{"id":"D4-078","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"hard","q":"A relying party accepts long-lived bearer tokens with no audience restriction. An attacker replays a token captured from another service. Which control most directly prevents this class of misuse?","options":["Longer token lifetimes for convenience","Audience-restricted, short-lived tokens with proof-of-possession/sender constraint","Storing tokens in browser local storage","Disabling token signature validation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Audience-restricted, short-lived tokens with proof-of-possession/sender constraint</strong> — binding tokens to an audience and to the sender, plus short lifetimes, defeats cross-service replay.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Longer token lifetimes for convenience</b>: longer lifetimes widen the replay window.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing tokens in browser local storage</b>: local storage is XSS-exposed and does nothing against replay.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling token signature validation</b>: turning off validation removes the last integrity check entirely.</span>"},{"id":"D4-079","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud app must scale stateless workloads and roll updates without downtime across many nodes. Which technology set best supports this application virtualization and orchestration goal?","options":["A single large monolith on one server","Manual SSH deployments to each host","Containers managed by an orchestrator with rolling deployments","Physical servers with quarterly patch windows"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Containers managed by an orchestrator with rolling deployments</strong> — containerized, orchestrated workloads enable horizontal scaling and zero-downtime rolling updates.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single large monolith on one server</b>: a single node cannot scale out or update without downtime.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual SSH deployments to each host</b>: manual per-host deploys are error-prone and not orchestrated.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical servers with quarterly patch windows</b>: slow physical cycles conflict with continuous, scalable delivery.</span>"},{"id":"D4-080","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"easy","q":"During third-party software management, why does license compliance matter to a cloud security program?","options":["Licenses determine server CPU speed","Licenses encrypt the application automatically","Licenses replace the need for vulnerability scanning","Non-compliant licenses can create legal exposure and force removal or costly relicensing of components"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Non-compliant licenses can create legal exposure and force removal or costly relicensing of components</strong> — license terms (e.g., copyleft) can impose obligations; violations create legal and operational risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Licenses determine server CPU speed</b>: licensing is a legal matter, not a performance setting.</span><span class='qd'><b>Licenses encrypt the application automatically</b>: licenses grant usage rights; they provide no encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Licenses replace the need for vulnerability scanning</b>: license compliance and vulnerability management are separate concerns.</span>"},{"id":"D4-081","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"A company wants centralized enforcement of conditional access (device posture, location, risk) before granting SSO to cloud apps. Where is this policy best enforced?","options":["At the identity provider as conditional/adaptive access policy","At each individual application separately","In the database tier","On the end-user's antivirus"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>At the identity provider as conditional/adaptive access policy</strong> — enforcing conditional access at the IdP applies consistent, centrally managed rules across all federated apps.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>At each individual application separately</b>: per-app enforcement is inconsistent and hard to maintain.</span><span class='qd'><b>In the database tier</b>: the database sees data access, not authentication context signals.</span><span class='qd'><b>On the end-user's antivirus</b>: AV cannot broker federated access decisions.</span>"},{"id":"D4-082","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"hard","q":"An architect must choose where to place a WAF, an API gateway, and mTLS in a microservices deployment. Which placement reflects sound defense-in-depth?","options":["WAF and gateway internal only; no service-to-service auth","WAF at the edge for web traffic, API gateway for API ingress policy, and mTLS between internal services","mTLS only at the edge, nothing internal","A single WAF replacing all other controls"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>WAF at the edge for web traffic, API gateway for API ingress policy, and mTLS between internal services</strong> — each control addresses a distinct layer: web attacks at the edge, API policy at ingress, and mutual authentication east-west.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>WAF and gateway internal only; no service-to-service auth</b>: leaving internal traffic unauthenticated abandons zero trust.</span><span class='qd'><b>mTLS only at the edge, nothing internal</b>: edge-only mTLS leaves east-west traffic unprotected.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single WAF replacing all other controls</b>: one control cannot cover API policy and internal mutual auth.</span>"},{"id":"D4-083","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud team wants to detect vulnerable and outdated open-source components introduced by developers as part of the build. Which testing type is purpose-built for this?","options":["Physical penetration testing","Load testing","Software composition analysis (SCA)","Chaos engineering"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Software composition analysis (SCA)</strong> — SCA inventories third-party and open-source components and flags known vulnerabilities and license issues in the build.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical penetration testing</b>: physical testing targets facilities, not software dependencies.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load testing</b>: load testing measures performance under stress, not component vulnerabilities.</span><span class='qd'><b>Chaos engineering</b>: chaos testing probes resilience to failures, not dependency risk.</span>"},{"id":"D4-084","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the strongest reason to prefer phishing-resistant MFA (e.g., FIDO2/WebAuthn) over SMS one-time codes?","options":["SMS is cheaper to operate","SMS codes never expire","FIDO2 removes the need for any identity provider","FIDO2 resists credential phishing and SIM-swap/interception attacks"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>FIDO2 resists credential phishing and SIM-swap/interception attacks</strong> — origin-bound public-key authentication is not replayable to a phishing site and does not depend on interceptable SMS.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SMS is cheaper to operate</b>: cost is not a security advantage and ignores SMS weaknesses.</span><span class='qd'><b>SMS codes never expire</b>: false, and non-expiry would be a weakness, not a benefit.</span><span class='qd'><b>FIDO2 removes the need for any identity provider</b>: FIDO2 is an authenticator, still used with an IdP.</span>"},{"id":"D4-085","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A design review flags that all microservices share one database with full read/write to every table. Which architectural improvement best supports least privilege and blast-radius reduction?","options":["Segment data ownership per service with scoped credentials and separate schemas/stores","Give every service the same admin DB credentials for simplicity","Remove all authentication to reduce latency","Store credentials in each service's source code"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Segment data ownership per service with scoped credentials and separate schemas/stores</strong> — scoping each service to only its data limits what a single compromise can reach.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Give every service the same admin DB credentials for simplicity</b>: shared admin access maximizes blast radius.</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove all authentication to reduce latency</b>: dropping auth abandons least privilege entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store credentials in each service's source code</b>: embedded secrets leak and do not address over-broad access.</span>"},{"id":"D4-086","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"hard","q":"A widely used upstream package is abandoned; its maintainer account is later taken over and a malicious update is published. Which control set best detects and prevents ingesting that update?","options":["Auto-update to the latest version immediately on release","Pin versions, verify signatures/checksums, review changelogs, and stage through an internal proxy with scanning","Trust the registry implicitly","Disable dependency management entirely"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Pin versions, verify signatures/checksums, review changelogs, and stage through an internal proxy with scanning</strong> — pinning plus integrity verification and gated promotion catches and blocks a poisoned update before it reaches production.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Auto-update to the latest version immediately on release</b>: blind auto-update is exactly how a poisoned release spreads.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trust the registry implicitly</b>: implicit trust is what account-takeover attacks exploit.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable dependency management entirely</b>: abandoning dependency management is impractical and creates worse gaps.</span>"},{"id":"D4-087","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"A SaaS provider wants enterprise customers to manage user lifecycle (create/disable) automatically from their own directory. Which standard best enables cross-domain user provisioning?","options":["SNMP","SMTP","SCIM","SFTP"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>SCIM</strong> — the System for Cross-domain Identity Management standardizes automated provisioning and deprovisioning of user identities between an IdP and SaaS apps.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>SNMP</b>: SNMP monitors network devices, not identity provisioning.</span><span class='qd'><b>SMTP</b>: SMTP transports email and has no identity lifecycle function.</span><span class='qd'><b>SFTP</b>: SFTP transfers files securely; it does not provision users.</span>"},{"id":"D4-088","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"hard","q":"A confidential-computing requirement mandates that data be protected even while in use during processing in a multi-tenant cloud. Which technology directly addresses data-in-use protection?","options":["Standard TLS 1.3","RAID storage","Full-disk encryption","Trusted execution environment (enclave) with memory encryption"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Trusted execution environment (enclave) with memory encryption</strong> — a TEE isolates and encrypts data during computation, protecting data-in-use from the host and other tenants.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Standard TLS 1.3</b>: TLS protects data in transit, not while being processed in memory.</span><span class='qd'><b>RAID storage</b>: RAID provides redundancy, not confidentiality of data in use.</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk encryption</b>: FDE protects data at rest, which is decrypted when in use.</span>"},{"id":"D4-089","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"easy","q":"Which practice best reflects using validated open-source software in a regulated cloud environment?","options":["Sourcing from a curated internal repository of vetted, version-pinned, scanned components","Pulling any package that solves the problem quickly","Disabling scanning to speed development","Copying code snippets from forums without attribution"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Sourcing from a curated internal repository of vetted, version-pinned, scanned components</strong> — a governed internal source ensures only reviewed, tracked, and scanned open-source enters the pipeline.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Pulling any package that solves the problem quickly</b>: ungoverned pulls introduce unvetted risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling scanning to speed development</b>: skipping scanning defeats validation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Copying code snippets from forums without attribution</b>: unreviewed forum code carries unknown security and license risk.</span>"},{"id":"D4-090","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"An organization discovers many employees using an unsanctioned file-sharing SaaS. Beyond blocking, leadership wants to understand usage and coach safe alternatives. Which CASB deployment mode best gives ongoing inline control and coaching?","options":["API-only (out-of-band) mode exclusively","Forward/reverse proxy (inline) mode","Disabling the CASB during business hours","Manual quarterly log review only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Forward/reverse proxy (inline) mode</strong> — inline proxy mode intercepts traffic in real time, enabling live policy enforcement, blocking, and user coaching prompts.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>API-only (out-of-band) mode exclusively</b>: API mode inspects after the fact and cannot enforce inline in real time.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling the CASB during business hours</b>: turning off the control removes protection when it is most needed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual quarterly log review only</b>: periodic review is not real-time control or coaching.</span>"},{"id":"D4-091","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud application must encrypt sensitive data with keys the customer controls and can revoke, even though the provider hosts the workload. Which key-management approach best meets this?","options":["Provider-managed keys with no customer visibility","Hard-coded symmetric key in the application","Customer-managed keys (BYOK/HYOK) via a key management service or HSM","No encryption, rely on physical security"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Customer-managed keys (BYOK/HYOK) via a key management service or HSM</strong> — customer-controlled keys let the customer govern access and revoke, providing cryptographic control over provider-hosted data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provider-managed keys with no customer visibility</b>: this removes the customer control the requirement demands.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hard-coded symmetric key in the application</b>: embedded keys cannot be revoked cleanly and are easily exposed.</span><span class='qd'><b>No encryption, rely on physical security</b>: forgoing encryption fails the confidentiality requirement.</span>"},{"id":"D4-092","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"medium","q":"An API is protected by authentication but an attacker changes the object ID in a request and retrieves another user's record. Which API risk is this, and the correct fix?","options":["Weak TLS; upgrade cipher suites","Log injection; sanitize log output","Clickjacking; add frame-busting headers","Broken object-level authorization (BOLA/IDOR); enforce per-object authorization checks server-side"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Broken object-level authorization (BOLA/IDOR); enforce per-object authorization checks server-side</strong> — authentication alone is insufficient; the server must verify the caller is authorized for the specific object requested.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Weak TLS; upgrade cipher suites</b>: the flaw is authorization logic, not transport encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Log injection; sanitize log output</b>: log handling is unrelated to object-access control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Clickjacking; add frame-busting headers</b>: clickjacking is a UI redress attack, not an ID-tampering data-access issue.</span>"},{"id":"D4-093","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"hard","q":"A federation trust is established, but the SP does not validate the assertion's audience or expiry. What is the most serious consequence, and the fix?","options":["Assertion replay/misuse across services; enforce audience restriction and NotOnOrAfter validation","Slower logins; add caching","Larger tokens; compress assertions","Broken CSS; adjust stylesheets"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Assertion replay/misuse across services; enforce audience restriction and NotOnOrAfter validation</strong> — without audience and expiry checks, assertions can be replayed or reused at unintended SPs; validating both closes the gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Slower logins; add caching</b>: performance is not the issue; this ignores the replay risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Larger tokens; compress assertions</b>: token size is irrelevant to authorization validation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Broken CSS; adjust stylesheets</b>: this is a security validation flaw, not a presentation bug.</span>"},{"id":"D4-094","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"easy","q":"What is the primary security purpose of placing sensitive workloads in separate namespaces or isolated runtime contexts?","options":["To improve font rendering","To provide logical isolation limiting cross-workload interference and access","To reduce electricity costs","To speed up DNS resolution"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To provide logical isolation limiting cross-workload interference and access</strong> — isolation boundaries constrain a compromised or misbehaving workload from affecting others.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To improve font rendering</b>: rendering is unrelated to workload isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>To reduce electricity costs</b>: isolation is a security/architecture concern, not an energy optimization.</span><span class='qd'><b>To speed up DNS resolution</b>: namespaces here are about isolation, not DNS performance.</span>"},{"id":"D4-095","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"hard","q":"To achieve stronger integrity assurance across the build pipeline, a team wants cryptographic evidence linking source, build steps, and artifacts. Which practice best delivers this provenance?","options":["Emailing a build log to auditors","Renaming artifacts with version numbers","Generating signed, verifiable build provenance/attestations (e.g., SLSA-style) with an SBOM","Storing artifacts on a shared drive"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Generating signed, verifiable build provenance/attestations (e.g., SLSA-style) with an SBOM</strong> — signed provenance ties artifacts to their source and build process, enabling tamper-evident verification.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Emailing a build log to auditors</b>: an emailed log is neither cryptographically verifiable nor tamper-evident.</span><span class='qd'><b>Renaming artifacts with version numbers</b>: naming is not integrity evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing artifacts on a shared drive</b>: storage location provides no provenance or signature.</span>"},{"id":"D4-096","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise wants immediate loss of access to all federated apps when an employee is terminated. Which IAM design best guarantees this?","options":["Rely on each SaaS app to eventually notice","Ask the employee to log out","Rotate the app's TLS certificate","Centralized identity lifecycle at the IdP with automated deprovisioning propagated via federation/SCIM"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Centralized identity lifecycle at the IdP with automated deprovisioning propagated via federation/SCIM</strong> — disabling the identity at the authoritative IdP and propagating it cuts access everywhere at once.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely on each SaaS app to eventually notice</b>: passive, delayed removal leaves active access windows.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ask the employee to log out</b>: a departing user cannot be trusted to revoke their own access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rotate the app's TLS certificate</b>: certificate rotation does not deprovision a user identity.</span>"},{"id":"D4-097","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"medium","q":"A public API experiences credential-stuffing and volumetric abuse. Which combination at the API gateway most directly mitigates this while preserving legitimate use?","options":["Rate limiting, anomaly-based throttling, and bot/credential-abuse detection","Remove authentication to reduce failed logins","Increase token lifetime to reduce re-auth","Return full stack traces to failed callers"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Rate limiting, anomaly-based throttling, and bot/credential-abuse detection</strong> — these gateway controls curb automated abuse volume and detect stuffing patterns without blocking normal traffic.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove authentication to reduce failed logins</b>: removing auth eliminates the very control being attacked.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase token lifetime to reduce re-auth</b>: longer tokens raise exposure and do not stop stuffing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Return full stack traces to failed callers</b>: leaking traces aids attackers and worsens the situation.</span>"},{"id":"D4-098","domain":4,"obj":"4.5","diff":"medium","q":"A procurement team is onboarding a new SaaS subprocessor that will handle regulated data. Which supply-chain step best precedes signing the contract?","options":["Skip due diligence to meet a deadline","Perform a vendor security assessment reviewing certifications, controls, and data handling","Ask the vendor to self-certify verbally","Assume the SaaS is secure because it is popular"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Perform a vendor security assessment reviewing certifications, controls, and data handling</strong> — assessing the subprocessor's attestations, controls, and data practices is essential supply-chain due diligence before commitment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Skip due diligence to meet a deadline</b>: schedule pressure does not justify onboarding unassessed risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ask the vendor to self-certify verbally</b>: unverifiable verbal claims are not assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume the SaaS is secure because it is popular</b>: popularity is not evidence of adequate controls.</span>"},{"id":"D4-099","domain":4,"obj":"4.6","diff":"hard","q":"A tenant-facing app allows customers to run reports that generate downstream requests. Security worries a crafted report could make the server fetch internal metadata endpoints. Which vulnerability and control apply?","options":["Cross-site scripting; content security policy","Weak passwords; complexity policy","Server-side request forgery (SSRF); egress allowlisting, metadata protection, and URL validation","Log tampering; write-once logs"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Server-side request forgery (SSRF); egress allowlisting, metadata protection, and URL validation</strong> — an attacker coercing the server to call internal endpoints is SSRF; restricting egress, protecting metadata services, and validating destinations mitigate it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cross-site scripting; content security policy</b>: XSS is client-side script injection, not server-initiated internal requests.</span><span class='qd'><b>Weak passwords; complexity policy</b>: this is a server-side request abuse, not a credential-strength issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Log tampering; write-once logs</b>: log integrity is unrelated to coerced outbound requests.</span>"},{"id":"D4-100","domain":4,"obj":"4.7","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud security architect must decide how service accounts authenticate to a managed database in production. Which choice best aligns with least privilege and secret hygiene?","options":["A shared password reused across all environments","Embedding the DB password in the container image","Granting the service account database owner rights for flexibility","Scoped workload identity with short-lived tokens retrieved from a secrets manager, no static secrets in code"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Scoped workload identity with short-lived tokens retrieved from a secrets manager, no static secrets in code</strong> — scoped identity plus dynamic short-lived credentials from a managed secrets store enforces least privilege and eliminates embedded secrets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A shared password reused across all environments</b>: reuse breaks isolation and accountability across environments.</span><span class='qd'><b>Embedding the DB password in the container image</b>: baked-in secrets leak with the image and cannot rotate cleanly.</span><span class='qd'><b>Granting the service account database owner rights for flexibility</b>: owner rights violate least privilege and widen blast radius.</span>"}]);
